## Three kernels to compare

Write three implementations of 256x256 matrix multiplication in `neon_bench.c`. All three compute the same result — the only difference is how they use the hardware.

### Kernel 1 — Scalar INT8 (no SIMD)

```C { line_numbers = "true" }
void matmul_scalar_int8(int8_t* A, int8_t* B, int32_t* C, int N) {
    for(int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        for(int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            int32_t sum = 0;
            for(int k = 0; k < N; k++)
                sum += (int32_t)A[i*N+k] * (int32_t)B[k*N+j];
            C[i*N+j] = sum;
        }
}
```

This is what most developers write. With `-O2`, the compiler tries to auto-vectorize but the widening requirement (INT8 to INT32) often causes scalar fallback or a suboptimal vectorization path.

### Kernel 2 — FP32 NEON using vmlaq_f32

```C { line_numbers = "true" }
#include <arm_neon.h>

void matmul_fp32_neon(float* A, float* B, float* C, int N) {
    for(int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        for(int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            float32x4_t sum = vdupq_n_f32(0.0f);
            for(int k = 0; k < N; k += 4) {
                float32x4_t a = vld1q_f32(&A[i*N + k]);
                float32x4_t b = vld1q_f32(&B[k*N + j]);
                sum = vmlaq_f32(sum, a, b);
            }
            float32x2_t lo = vget_low_f32(sum);
            float32x2_t hi = vget_high_f32(sum);
            float32x2_t s  = vadd_f32(lo, hi);
            s = vpadd_f32(s, s);
            C[i*N+j] = vget_lane_f32(s, 0);
        }
}
```

`vmlaq_f32` processes 4 FP32 values per instruction with native 32-bit accumulation. No widening is needed — the result of FP32 x FP32 fits directly in a FP32 register.

### Kernel 3 — INT8 NEON using vmull_s8

```C { line_numbers = "true" }
void matmul_int8_neon(int8_t* A, int8_t* B, int32_t* C, int N) {
    for(int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        for(int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
            int32x4_t sum = vdupq_n_s32(0);
            for(int k = 0; k < N; k += 8) {
                int8x8_t  a   = vld1_s8(&A[i*N + k]);
                int8x8_t  b   = vld1_s8(&B[k*N + j]);
                int16x8_t mul = vmull_s8(a, b);
                sum = vpadalq_s16(sum, mul);
            }
            int32x2_t lo = vget_low_s32(sum);
            int32x2_t hi = vget_high_s32(sum);
            int32x2_t s  = vadd_s32(lo, hi);
            s = vpadd_s32(s, s);
            C[i*N+j] = vget_lane_s32(s, 0);
        }
}
```

`vmull_s8` processes 8 INT8 pairs per instruction producing INT16 intermediate results. `vpadalq_s16` then pair-adds these into the INT32 accumulator. This is the explicit widening chain — two instructions where FP32 uses one — but processing 8 pairs vs FP32's 4.

## Prevent dead code elimination

When benchmarking with `-O2`, always print a value from the result array. Without this the compiler detects that the output is never used and eliminates the entire computation. All timings will show 0.00ms.

```C
printf("Checksum: %d\n", C[0] + C[N*N-1]);
```

## Time each kernel using CLOCK_MONOTONIC

Use `CLOCK_MONOTONIC` for nanosecond-resolution timing on Android. The standard `clock()` function has only 10ms resolution on Android 4.x and is not suitable for benchmarking.

```C { line_numbers = "true" }
double get_ms() {
    struct timespec ts;
    clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, &ts);
    return ts.tv_sec * 1000.0 + ts.tv_nsec / 1000000.0;
}

double t0 = get_ms();
matmul_fp32_neon(Af, Bf, Cf, N);
double elapsed = get_ms() - t0;
printf("FP32 NEON: %.2f ms\n", elapsed);
```

Run 2 warmup iterations before timing to allow TFLite JIT compilation and CPU cache to stabilize, then record 10 timed runs.
